Exploratory Analysis

Introduction

Suicide and beer consumption is always a serious concern in our society. However, drinking beer is not only related to a negative outcome but also represents a signifier of happiness. Therefore, we are interested in the relationship between beer consumption and happiness score by a different country. Moreover, we provide two charts. One of the charts presents the top 20 countries of beer consumption and a map that represents the global suicide rate.

Summary

The summary information is shown below as lists. There are 183 countries in suicide_rate_2016 data set. The country with the lowest suicide rate in 2016 is Antigua and Barbuda. Besides, the country that rank #1 in happiness is Denmark with the score of 7.526. Last, we found that with the highest happiness score, the beer consumption is 224 Liter per Capita.

Table

This table provides information on the suicide rate, beer consumption, happiness score, and happiness rank by countries. By creating this table, it is easier for us to organize the relationship between those factors.

Chart

Chart one is a world map intend to show the suicide rate per 100,000 population around the world. From the chart we can see that Russia has high level of suicide rate, and countries in global South has relative lower suicide rate than countries in the North.

Chart two is a scatter plot that shows the relationship between the average happiness score and liters of beer consumption per capita. From the chart, we can see that there are some weak positive association between the x and the y variable. Higher beer consumption have slight correlation with higher average happiness score.

Chart three is a bar chart that shows the top 20 countries with most beer consumption. We see that Namibia is the country with most beer consumption per capita.
